    notes:
      "## Clinical Context — The TRT Adjunct Workhorse\n\nhCG is the foundational TRT adjunct compound for testicular function preservation and fertility preservation. The use case is mechanistically straightforward: exogenous testosterone suppresses the hypothalamic-pituitary axis, suppressing endogenous LH, suppressing intratesticular testosterone production, producing testicular atrophy and impaired spermatogenesis. hCG directly activates the Leydig-cell LH receptors — bypassing the suppressed pituitary — to maintain intratesticular testosterone production at levels supporting testicular volume and fertility.\n\nDecades of clinical practice support hCG as the gold-standard approach. Modern TRT clinics routinely include hCG as a standard adjunct option for users who prioritize fertility preservation, testicular volume preservation, or both. The concurrent E2 management consideration (hCG-driven testicular aromatase activity adds to TRT-driven peripheral aromatization) is the principal practical complication.\n\n## Pharmaceutical Formulations\n\n### Pregnyl (Organon, urinary-derived hCG, IM)\n- 5000 IU and 10000 IU vial sizes typical\n- Reconstitute with packaged diluent (or BAC water for off-label TRT adjunct preparation)\n- IM injection per pharmaceutical labeling; SubQ administration is widely used in TRT adjunct contexts off-label\n- Most commonly prescribed urinary-derived product in TRT adjunct contexts\n\n### Novarel (Ferring, urinary-derived hCG, IM)\n- 10000 IU vial size\n- Equivalent product to Pregnyl in clinical practice\n\n### Ovidrel (Merck, recombinant choriogonadotropin alfa, SubQ)\n- Pre-filled SubQ syringe; 250 mcg (~6500 IU equivalent)\n- Recombinant — cleaner product without urinary-derived protein content\n- Higher cost per unit vs urinary-derived options; less commonly used in TRT adjunct contexts due to cost\n- Preferred in fertility medicine where reliability and consistency are paramount\n\n## Dose Range — TRT Adjunct vs Fertility Medicine\n\nThe TRT adjunct dose range and fertility medicine dose range differ substantially.\n\n**TRT adjunct typical range:** 250-500 IU SubQ 2-3x weekly. Sufficient to maintain testicular volume and basal spermatogenesis in most users on stable testosterone protocols. Higher doses may produce greater testicular volume restoration in users with substantial pre-existing atrophy.\n\n**HPG axis restart range:** 1500-3000 IU 3x weekly during defined 8-12 week restart phase, typically combined with SERMs (enclomiphene, clomiphene, tamoxifen) to drive HPG axis recovery.\n\n**Fertility medicine range:** 1500-10000 IU per dose with variable scheduling per protocol; combined with FSH-active preparations (recombinant FSH or hMG) for spermatogenesis stimulation in hypogonadotropic hypogonadism; ovulation triggering in IVF protocols.\n\n## Estradiol Management — The Principal Practical Complication\n\nhCG-driven Leydig cell activity produces both testosterone AND estradiol via testicular aromatase. In TRT adjunct contexts, this adds to peripheral aromatization from exogenous testosterone — total aromatization burden is higher on TRT + hCG vs TRT alone at equivalent total testosterone exposure.\n\nPractical implications:\n- Estradiol monitoring is essential — sensitive E2 assay (LC-MS/MS) preferred over standard immunoassay\n- Some users require aromatase inhibitor (anastrozole, letrozole) coordination in TRT + hCG protocols where TRT alone did not require AI\n- Gynecomastia and water retention are the principal user-facing E2-related concerns\n- Dose-dependent — lower hCG doses produce less E2 burden\n\n## SubQ vs IM Administration\n\nPharmaceutical labeling specifies IM for Pregnyl and Novarel. Clinical practice routinely uses SubQ administration off-label — pharmacokinetics are essentially equivalent, SubQ is more convenient for self-administration, and SubQ is the preferred route in modern TRT/wellness clinic networks. Ovidrel pre-filled syringe is labeled for SubQ.\n\n## Synergies\n**Testosterone esters (cypionate, enanthate, propionate, undecanoate, topical)** — primary TRT context for hCG adjunct use. **Aromatase inhibitors (anastrozole, letrozole)** for E2 management in TRT + hCG combinations. **SERMs (enclomiphene, clomiphene, tamoxifen)** for HPG axis support and restart protocols. **hMG** for fertility medicine combinations targeting both LH and FSH receptor activity. **Comprehensive nutrition** with adequate protein and micronutrient support.\n\n## HPG Axis Restart — The PCT Context\n\nUsers transitioning off TRT or completing anabolic cycles use hCG as a component of HPG axis restart protocols. Standard restart approach combines:\n- hCG 1500-3000 IU 3x weekly × 4-6 weeks (Leydig cell stimulation to restore testicular volume and function)\n- SERM (enclomiphene 12.5-25mg daily, or clomiphene 25-50mg daily, or tamoxifen 10-20mg daily) × 6-8 weeks (pituitary LH/FSH recovery)\n- Tapered withdrawal of hCG followed by SERM continuation alone\n\nProtocol specifics vary substantially by provider; coordinate with knowledgeable endocrinologist or TRT/wellness clinic. The catalog does not provide specific protocol guidance per locked HRT rule.\n\n## WADA / Sport Considerations\n\nhCG is BANNED by WADA in male athletes — both at all times (in-competition and out-of-competition) and across testing methods. Testing detects both urinary-derived and recombinant hCG. Athletes subject to drug testing should not use hCG without TUE (Therapeutic Use Exemption) approval; even with TUE, WADA scrutiny is substantial. Female athletes are not subject to the male-specific hCG ban but should check sport-specific rules.\n\n## Evidence Quality\nMechanism well-established via decades of LH-receptor pharmacology research. Clinical evidence base for fertility medicine indications substantial — hCG has been in clinical use since the 1930s. Clinical evidence base for TRT adjunct use is largely real-world clinical practice rather than randomized trials, but the practice has decades of consistent application. Modern endocrinology and TRT/wellness clinic literature supports hCG as standard TRT adjunct.\n\n## Research vs Anecdote\nResearch: foundational LH-receptor pharmacology; FDA approval for fertility indications; substantial clinical practice base in TRT adjunct contexts (largely real-world rather than RCT-based). Anecdote: foundational TRT adjunct in modern clinical practice; community familiarity with dosing patterns and E2 management; historically the most commonly used TRT adjunct compound. Decision frame: foundational TRT adjunct for testicular function and fertility preservation; pharmaceutical-grade product preferred over compounding alternatives; estradiol management is the principal practical complication; combination with SERMs is standard for HPG axis restart applications; WADA-banned for male athletes — TUE required if applicable.",
