    notes:
      "## Clinical Context — The Fertility Induction Workhorse\n\nhMG occupies a distinct clinical niche from hCG. Where hCG is the foundational TRT adjunct for testicular volume and basal fertility preservation, hMG is the fertility induction compound used when complete spermatogenesis restoration requires both LH and FSH receptor activity. The combination of hCG (LH activity) + hMG (FSH activity) is the gold-standard fertility induction protocol for male hypogonadotropic hypogonadism — both congenital (Kallmann syndrome and isolated forms) and acquired (post-TRT, post-anabolic cycle, post-pituitary lesion).\n\nIn TRT adjunct contexts where the user's primary goal is fertility maintenance or testicular volume preservation, hCG monotherapy is generally sufficient. hMG addition is reserved for users with documented inadequate spermatogenesis on hCG monotherapy or users prioritizing aggressive fertility induction within a defined fertility window.\n\n## Pharmaceutical Formulations\n\n### Menopur (Ferring, highly-purified urinary hMG)\n- 75 IU and 150 IU vial sizes\n- Reconstitute with packaged diluent or BAC water for off-label preparation\n- Modern standard for urinary hMG — highly-purified to remove non-gonadotropin urinary proteins\n- SubQ administration\n- Predominant FSH activity supplemented with hCG to provide LH equivalence\n\n### Recombinant Alternatives\n**Gonal-F (Merck, recombinant FSH)** — pure FSH activity; no LH; combined with separate LH source if needed\n**Follistim (Organon, recombinant FSH)** — equivalent to Gonal-F in clinical practice\n**Luveris (Merck, recombinant LH)** — pure LH activity; combined with FSH source\n**Pergoveris (Merck, rFSH + rLH fixed combination)** — combined recombinant product equivalent to hMG functionality without urinary-derived content\n\nRecombinant products avoid urinary-derived protein content (relevant for users with documented sensitivity) but at substantially higher cost.\n\n### Repronex (older urinary hMG)\n- Less commonly used in modern fertility medicine practice\n- Replaced largely by Menopur in clinical workflows\n\n## Combined Protocol — hCG + hMG for Fertility Induction\n\nStandard fertility induction approach in male hypogonadotropic hypogonadism:\n- hCG 1500-3000 IU SubQ 2-3x weekly (Leydig cell stimulation, intratesticular testosterone)\n- Add hMG 75-150 IU SubQ 3x weekly after 6+ months of hCG monotherapy (Sertoli cell stimulation, complete spermatogenesis support)\n- Some protocols start hCG + hMG concurrently rather than sequential\n- Continue 3-6+ months with semen analysis monitoring\n- Discontinue or transition to maintenance protocol after fertility goals achieved\n\n## Spermatogenesis Timeline\n\nComplete spermatogenesis from spermatogonial stem cell to mature spermatozoa takes ~70 days. Semen analysis improvements are typically observed at 3-6 month checkpoints rather than weeks. Users on fertility induction protocols should plan for 6-12 month timelines from protocol initiation to documented fertility outcomes.\n\n## Synergies\n**hCG** — primary partner for combined LH + FSH receptor activity in fertility induction. **Aromatase inhibitors (anastrozole)** for E2 management in extended hCG + hMG protocols. **SERMs (enclomiphene, clomiphene, tamoxifen)** for HPG axis support; combination with hCG + hMG protocols varies by clinical context. **Comprehensive nutrition** with adequate protein, zinc, selenium, and antioxidant micronutrients (relevant to spermatogenesis).\n\n## TRT Adjunct vs Fertility Induction Context\n\nThe TRT adjunct context (testicular volume preservation, basal fertility maintenance) is well-served by hCG monotherapy in most cases. hMG addition is reserved for:\n- Users with documented inadequate spermatogenesis on hCG monotherapy after 6+ months\n- Users prioritizing aggressive fertility induction within a defined fertility window\n- Users with hypogonadotropic hypogonadism baseline (where hCG alone is insufficient even pre-TRT)\n- Users transitioning off TRT for fertility purposes (combined hCG + hMG during TRT cessation phase)\n\nThe additional cost and complexity of hMG addition is the principal practical consideration vs hCG monotherapy.\n\n## WADA / Sport Considerations\n\nGonadotropin preparations (hCG, hMG, recombinant gonadotropins) are BANNED by WADA in male athletes. Athletes subject to drug testing should not use hMG without TUE (Therapeutic Use Exemption) approval; even with TUE, scrutiny is substantial. Female athletes are not subject to the male-specific gonadotropin ban but should check sport-specific rules.\n\n## Evidence Quality\nMechanism well-established via decades of FSH and LH receptor pharmacology research. Clinical evidence base for fertility medicine indications substantial — gonadotropin preparations have been in clinical use since the 1960s. Combined hCG + hMG protocol for male hypogonadotropic hypogonadism has decades of consistent clinical support.\n\n## Research vs Anecdote\nResearch: foundational FSH + LH receptor pharmacology; FDA approval for fertility indications; substantial clinical evidence base for combined hCG + hMG fertility induction protocols. Anecdote: less commonly used in TRT adjunct contexts than hCG monotherapy due to cost and complexity; community familiarity in TRT contexts is modest. Decision frame: gonadotropin compound providing combined FSH + LH activity; principal use case is fertility induction in male hypogonadotropic hypogonadism (combined with hCG); not a routine TRT adjunct at the basal level (hCG monotherapy is generally sufficient); pharmaceutical-grade product preferred; estradiol management important in extended protocols; WADA-banned for male athletes.",
