    mechanism:
      "Modified analog of human insulin-like growth factor 1 (IGF-1) — a 70-amino-acid peptide hormone — engineered with two structural modifications that dramatically alter pharmacokinetics: (1) **N-terminal extension** with a 13-amino-acid sequence ('Long-' prefix), and (2) **substitution of glutamate at position 3 with arginine** ('-Arg3' suffix). These modifications combined reduce binding affinity to IGFBPs (insulin-like growth factor binding proteins, primarily IGFBP-3) by approximately 100-fold and extend plasma half-life from ~10-15 minutes (free native IGF-1) to ~20-30 hours (IGF-1 LR3). The pharmacokinetic shift is the central engineering rationale — native IGF-1 is approximately 99% bound to IGFBPs in circulation with very short free-form half-life, limiting practical pharmacological use; IGF-1 LR3's reduced IGFBP binding produces substantially more free-form IGF-1 available for receptor binding and substantially longer pharmacological exposure. **Mechanism — IGF-1 receptor (IGF-1R) agonism (the central effect)**: IGF-1 LR3 binds and activates the IGF-1 receptor, a tyrosine kinase receptor structurally homologous to the insulin receptor and expressed on most tissues including skeletal muscle, hepatocytes, neurons, adipocytes, immune cells, and the gut epithelium. IGF-1R activation drives downstream signaling via the PI3K/AKT/mTOR pathway (the canonical anabolic and anti-apoptotic pathway), the MAPK pathway (cell proliferation), and others. **Mechanism — anabolic effects on skeletal muscle**: IGF-1R activation on skeletal muscle drives protein synthesis via mTOR pathway activation, satellite cell proliferation and activation (claimed substrate for hyperplasia, though hyperplasia in adult skeletal muscle remains contested), anti-apoptotic effects on muscle fibers, and increased glucose uptake. The skeletal muscle effects are the principal use case driving research peptide community interest in IGF-1 LR3 for muscle hypertrophy. **Mechanism — insulin-like effects at high concentrations**: at high concentrations, IGF-1 cross-binds to the insulin receptor with reduced affinity but functionally significant activity, producing insulin-like effects on glucose uptake and lipogenesis. The cross-binding is the principal mechanism behind hypoglycemia as the main clinically meaningful side effect of IGF-1 LR3 use. **Mechanism — anti-apoptotic and cell proliferation effects (the mitogenic concern)**: IGF-1R activation produces anti-apoptotic and pro-proliferation effects across tissue types. The mitogenic mechanism is the substrate for the theoretical malignancy-promotion concern associated with elevated IGF-1 signaling — both endogenous (e.g., acromegaly, where pituitary GH excess drives sustained IGF-1 elevation) and exogenous (HGH or IGF-1 LR3 administration). The clinical evidence on supraphysiologic IGF-1 and malignancy risk is debated and context-dependent. **Mechanism — vs full-molecule HGH and GH peptides**: HGH-191AA stimulates hepatic IGF-1 production via GH receptor activation; GH peptides (CJC-1295, ipamorelin, etc.) stimulate endogenous pituitary GH which then produces hepatic IGF-1; IGF-1 LR3 IS the IGF-1 itself, bypassing both pituitary and hepatic synthesis. The downstream commonality is IGF-1 receptor activation; IGF-1 LR3 produces this effect more directly with extended pharmacokinetics vs the upstream alternatives. **Mechanism — vs native IGF-1 (Increlex / mecasermin)**: Increlex (mecasermin) is FDA-approved recombinant human IGF-1 for severe primary IGF-1 deficiency; it is bioidentical to native IGF-1 with normal IGFBP binding and short half-life requiring twice-daily dosing. IGF-1 LR3 is the structural variant with modified PK; it is NOT pharmaceutically approved. **Pharmaceutical status**: IGF-1 LR3 is NOT FDA-approved; research peptide format is the available form. Native IGF-1 (mecasermin) is approved as Increlex (Ipsen) for severe primary IGF-1 deficiency. **Pharmacokinetics**: half-life ~20-30 hours; daily SubQ dosing typical; some research peptide community protocols use site-injection patterns claiming localized hypertrophy effects (mechanism contested).",
